The '''<U+00D6>lschnitz''' is a right-bank, northern [[headstream]] of the [[White Main]] in the German state of Bavaria. It is a {{convert|18.5|km|mi}} long.

== Course ==
The <U+00D6>lschnitz has its source with a [[impoundment]] and granite well stone in Solg, a village in the borough of [[M<U+00FC>nchberg]]. It discharges into the White Main near [[Bad Berneck|Bad&nbsp;Berneck]].
The <U+00D6>lschnitz flows from Solg through a wide depression to the village of <U+00D6>lschnitz, to Tennersreuth, passes under the  [[Bundesautobahn A 9|A 9 motorway]], supplies water for the Streitau Mill and continues to B<U+00F6>seneck. From here the valley, through which the little river snakes, becomes ever narrower. After many river bends it reaches the Entenm<U+00FC>hle ("duck mill"), then flows around the hill spur near Stein in a large curve before cutting through the hard, [[diabase]] rock in a steep, rocky, narrow valley, rich in flora, and reaching the spa park (''Kurpark'') at Bad Berneck. After almost 19 km it discharges into the White Main. The <U+00D6>lschnitz valley between the ''Entenm<U+00FC>hle'' and Bad Berneck, through which the ''Westweg'' and ''Jean-Paul-Weg'' trails also run, is one of the most beautiful valleys in the Fichtelgebirge.

== Economic utlisation ==
Along the course of the stream, water power was used to driver many mill wheels. In 1536 the townsfolk of Berneck were giving fishing rights in the ''<U+00D6>lsnitz'' and, in 1692, it is described as the "best trout stream in the Fichtelberge".  In 1732 a protection ordinance was issued by the [[Margrave of Bayreuth]] for the <U+00D6>lschnitz for the [[freshwater pearl mussel]]s introduced there. Between 1733 and 1810, 6,000 pearls were harvested. Pearl fishing came under the supervision of a pearl inspector and, after 1810, the Bavarian Forestry Department.

